2-31 00:00:00',3750,'https://scontent-bom1-1.xx.fbcdn.net/v/t31.0-8/23509166_1199955093438376_6328500832988072646_o.jpg?oh=bc575e0ffbc065ee2432ad768fac6866&oe=5A89B6EE',0),(22,'Chasing The Blood Moon!','<p><span style=\"color: rgb(75, 79, 86); font-family: Helvetica, Arial, sans-serif; font-size: 14px; letter-spacing: normal;\">A rare total lunar eclipse that involves the second full moon of the month - popularly referred to as a Blue Moon - is set to take place on January 31 for the first time in over 150 years.</span><br style=\"color: rgb(75, 79, 86); font-family: Helvetica, Arial, sans-serif; font-size: 14px; letter-spacing: normal;\"><span style=\"color: rgb(75, 79, 86); font-family: Helvetica, Arial, sans-serif; font-size: 14px; letter-spacing: normal;\">This will be the first eclipse of 2018. For the Indian subcontinent, the Middle East and Eastern Europe, the eclipse will already be underway as the Moon rises above the horizon.</span><br style=\"color: rgb(75, 79, 86); font-family: Helvetica, Arial, sans-serif; font-size: 14px; letter-spacing: normal;\"><span style=\"color: rgb(75, 79, 86); font-family: Helvetica, Arial, sans-serif; font-size: 14px; letter-spacing: normal;\">Total eclipses are a freak of cosmic happenstance. Ever since the moon formed, about 4.5 billion years ago, it has been inching away from our planet (by about 1.6 inches, or 4 centimeters per year). The setup right now is perfect: the moon is at the perfect distance for Earth\'s shadow to cover the moon totally, but just barely. Billions of years from</span><span class=\"text_exposed_show\" style=\"display: inline; font-family: Helvetica, Arial, sans-serif; color: rgb(75, 79, 86); font-size: 14px; letter-spacing: normal;\">&nbsp;now, that won\'t be the case.<br><br>The cosmos loving team at Mapping Journeys has decided to explore this incredible phenomena.<br>Here in Mumbai the Penumbral Eclipse will begin at 16.21hrs, the Penumbral, Partial and Full eclipse will not be visible as the Moon will be hiding below the horizon line. The Maximum eclipse begins at 18.59hrs and this will be visible as the moon will be above the horizon by this time.<br>We have decided to apply a Cheat Code in an attempt to rope in partial and total eclipse as well.<br><br>How is this possible?<br>It\'s pretty simple and requires some basic calculations. At sea level an average person can see as far as 5km in all directions which means the horizon line will be 5km away.<br>The same average person if he/she climbs up to 1875ft the distance visibility to the horizon jumps to approx 85km in all directions.<br>Manikgad fort happens to be exactly at this height and is our next door neighbour to our Moksh Mantra campsite. Unlike on the ground at this height the North East line will be clear off buildings, tower and other obstructions further increasing our chances to see a Moonrise even before it actually rises.<br><br>The plan:<br>Check in: Day 1, 10am<br>Check out: Day 2, 11am<br><br>Once at the campsite we proceed for lunch and after some rest we start the trek to Manikgad. The trek to the top takes 2hrs-2.5hrs approx. Here we pitch our tents and set up the place for the night that awaits and obviouly the Moon show.<br>Dinner will be served at the top itself.&nbsp;<br>Next morning we again take advantage of the height to see the Sun rising up before those who will see the Sunrise few minutes later.<br>Time to wrap up the site and trek back down to the campsite where breakfast will be served.<br>After breakfast the event concludes and the return journey back to the sea level (city) begins :D<br><br>Cost:Rs. 1350/- per person.<br><br>Inclusions:<br>Meals: Day 1: Lunch and Dinner. Day 2: Breakfast.<br>Tent stay (2/4 sharing basis).<br>Safety and First Aid.<br>Professional expertise.<br>Guide charges.<br>Mapping Journeys charges.&nbsp;<br>Campsite entry charges.<br><br>Exclusions:<br>Personal expenses.<br>Insurance of any kind.<br>Medical hospitalization, evacuation and related expenses.<br>Any item not covered under “inclusions”.<br><br>Smoking and consumption of alcohol is strictly prohibited. For confirmation of the seat, full amount needs to be deposited prior to the event<br><br>Payment options:<br>*Do confirm about the seat availability prior to any payments.*<br><br>-For payment using credit/debit card/net-banking:<br><a href=\"https://l.facebook.com/l.php?u=http%3A%2F%2Fgo.eventshigh.com%2Fmappingjourneys&amp;h=ATNB3LVIABe_NFZqKjZHfAzrwleEPVoGWD3EpkaH6c2TxblRcgiri_efyvlPSVnTmSbteOZ3zm0JM92YEgWx7i0dZRMRwZxKQA3WqU4PMKNg64czO3TDRK3W9rGeglnIgauhm6mD4caIjPE-XQ5iA9wHWZFSpLwM8Hog0PRI65KgiWgSje0\" rel=\"nofollow noopener\" target=\"_blank\" data-lynx-mode=\"async\" style=\"color: rgb(54, 88, 153); font-family: inherit;\"><span style=\"font-family: inherit;\">http://go.eventshigh.com/</span><wbr><span class=\"word_break\" style=\"display: inline-block; font-family: inherit;\"></span>mappingjourneys</a><br><br>Terms and Conditions and Cancellation Policy:&nbsp;<a href=\"https://l.facebook.com/l.php?u=http%3A%2F%2Fmappingjourneys.com%2Fterms_and_conditions.html&amp;h=ATPEMFOYgGeaqztJVCdxs4eKdfwlZn2Proivx1sHSQYNpPLYgKLeKSYiqYYejxRpjJDCcvEdfgR_3X1N9NYT3ddwbC3jwQLpkrtSeStUF8Idg60zROnunzBwaK_eg6ecNi6oxeeQxY8d4sD6aCaimU4wHKvYfICqHZqEME7QqijyZNbHVGU\" rel=\"nofollow noopener\" target=\"_blank\" data-lynx-mode=\"async\" style=\"color: rgb(54, 88, 153); font-family: inherit;\"><span style=\"font-family: inherit;\">http://</span><wbr><span class=\"word_break\" style=\"display: inline-block; font-family: inherit;\"></span><span style=\"font-family: inherit;\">mappingjourneys.com/</span><wbr><span class=\"word_break\" style=\"display: inline-block; font-family: inherit;\"></span>terms_and_conditions.html</a><br><br>For other payment options, queries and registration, please contact:+91 9867697306<br>+91 9867693107<br><br>travel@mappingjourneys.com<br><br>Directions:<br>Mumbai Pune expressway<br>Take Khalapur exit – immediately after toll<br>From Pali naka, go straight towards Pen<br>Take right from Varsai Naka<br>20 min from here you will reach the campsite<br><br>Or here is the google maps link(advised to save maps offline):<a href=\"https://goo.gl/maps/8CC9KEvvg7P2\" rel=\"nofollow noopener\" target=\"_blank\" data-lynx-mode=\"async\" data-lynx-uri=\"https://l.facebook.com/l.php?u=https%3A%2F%2Fgoo.gl%2Fmaps%2F8CC9KEvvg7P2&amp;h=ATNpujC5CX36e_6F_zQBOO_Dmam0JrVXiGxEXrfprHV2Kng2oXm-ICT7aLMvrfo7STJpY_C_k7vE_ezx-QQ5_kAEuqEnLjc0OaE1NB0A2P9ippcuSk7LrX50N7VoNcTDpYevSVm6Ck83tNFTPbbZ0dI78pCe6hafgGxl6sK6qkea213mqa8\" style=\"color: rgb(54, 88, 153); font-family: inherit;\"><span style=\"font-family: inherit;\">https://goo.gl/maps/</span><wbr><span class=\"word_break\" style=\"display: inline-block; font-family: inherit;\"></span>8CC9KEvvg7P2</a></span><br></p>','2018-01-31 00:00:00',1350,'https://scontent.fbom2-1.fna.fbcdn.net/v/t1.0-9/26169457_1246843335416218_6668769754583381553_n.jpg?oh=b974e8c66d895bcd3b74fcecd1291f89&oe=5AEE10AC',0),(23,'Sandhan Valley Trek - Batch 4','<p><span style=\"color: rgb(75, 79, 86); font-family: Helvetica, Arial, sans-serif; font-size: 14px; letter-spacing: normal;\"><b>Team Mapping Journeys!</b></span><br style=\"color: rgb(75, 79, 86); font-family: Helvetica, Arial, sans-serif; font-size: 14px; letter-spacing: normal;\"><span style=\"color: rgb(75, 79, 86); font-family: Helvetica, Arial, sans-serif; font-size: 14px; letter-spacing: normal;\">“Anything that gets your blood racing is probably worth doing.”&nbsp;</span><br style=\"color: rgb(75, 79, 86); font-family: Helvetica, Arial, sans-serif; font-size: 14px; letter-spacing: normal;\"><br style=\"color: rgb(75, 79, 86); font-family: Helvetica, Arial, sans-serif; font-size: 14px; letter-spacing: normal;\"><span style=\"color: rgb(75, 79, 86); font-family: Helvetica, Arial, sans-serif; font-size: 14px; letter-spacing: normal;\">Situated in the Western Ghats near Ratangad and popularly known as the Valley Of Shadows, Sandhan Valley is a naturally carved valley 200 feet deep and approximately 2kms long. Located near to the stunning Bhandardara region, it is also surrounded by Alang, Madan, Kulang, Kalsubai, Ratangad and Ajoba forts.</span><br style=\"color: rgb(75, 79, 86); font-family: Helvetica, Arial, sans-serif; font-size: 14px; letter-spacing: normal;\"><br style=\"color: rgb(75, 79, 86); font-family: Helvetica, Arial, sans-serif; font-size: 14px; letter-spacing: normal;\"><span style=\"color: rgb(75, 79, 86); font-family: Helvetica, Arial, sans-serif; font-size: 14px; letter-spacing: normal;\">During the monsoons, the valley remains closed for trekking due to falling of rock and numerous waterfalls that block the way inside the valley. It becomes a must-do trek after monsoons for its outstanding views and rough patches. The trek begins at Kasara and ends at Asangaon station. Entry point of the valley is at a&nbsp;</span><span class=\"text_exposed_show\" style=\"display: inline; font-family: Helvetica, Arial, sans-serif; color: rgb(75, 79, 86); font-size: 14px; letter-spacing: normal;\">village called Samrad and the valley exits into a village called Dehene.<br><br>Sandhan valley is a full descend trek, but the descend is not an easy walk. Completing the trek is more like solving a boulder puzzle. Throughout the length of the valley, we come across boulders ranging in sizes that we need to tackle as we proceed ahead. This trek cannot be done without technical assistance of certified professionals as there are three patches where one has to rappel down. The 45ft rappelling patch along with two others requiring assistance only add to the thrill of the exploration.<br><br>Sandhan is not recommended for people who are not physically fit/active. The length to be covered in two days is 10km. We highly recommend checking the photos and video link provided below before registering for the trek.<br><br>Dates: February 3rd-4th(Departure on the night of 5nd)<br>Height: 4100 ft.<br>Grade: Above Medium. (Not recommended for people trekking for the first time)<br>Location: Bhandardara Region.<br><br>Album Link:&nbsp;<a href=\"https://goo.gl/photos/fiz7xPtojqQxjybe8\" rel=\"nofollow noopener\" target=\"_blank\" data-lynx-mode=\"async\" data-lynx-uri=\"https://l.facebook.com/l.php?u=https%3A%2F%2Fgoo.gl%2Fphotos%2Ffiz7xPtojqQxjybe8&amp;h=ATOC7wbl8Ib9hzqqtyCVqKrbpHsLf-PRUIS4u8bZQ_4uBM6r7NSHD86_Ek_NhlU0X464FaDdvzd5fxtK5k__MR8aKFP83Tt6fB1l7feeaGli89eDEifB7feQmcczSenomb3mEkIlsW7z-abgdgzqQ5smGJVmfnN_rgbebvnYF60Y-CFrYI4\" style=\"color: rgb(54, 88, 153); font-family: inherit;\"><span style=\"font-family: inherit;\">https://goo.gl/photos/</span><wbr><span class=\"word_break\" style=\"display: inline-block; font-family: inherit;\"></span>fiz7xPtojqQxjybe8</a><br>Video Link:&nbsp;<a href=\"https://l.facebook.com/l.php?u=https%3A%2F%2Fyoutu.be%2FvLR7gdmFYTE&amp;h=ATPy_vjd4UHagDTFmLgJIh_wZF3vrwqrjBM17Ihq79SpkYByArhl4AvLjlYGOTbGJUJSOO1ta9qU79Rb6gHTl8MVBUsissfnp7aqmV8qPomZ5mgCnqtur-TaiE4nHmFg49zi6YptrimJp_0GH-1Cm0yagz9lR_dr2sOBjbzbXDZLr41DnCc\" rel=\"nofollow noopener\" target=\"_blank\" data-lynx-mode=\"async\" style=\"color: rgb(54, 88, 153); font-family: inherit;\"><span style=\"font-family: inherit;\">https://youtu.be/</span><wbr><span class=\"word_break\" style=\"display: inline-block; font-family: inherit;\"></span>vLR7gdmFYTE</a><br><br><b>Itinerary:</b><br>2nd February (Friday Night):<br>Catch the CST-Kasara train as per the timings mentioned.<br>10:50 pm - CST.<br>10:57 pm - Byculla.<br>11:05 pm - Dadar.<br>11:13 pm - Kurla.<br>11:18 pm - Ghatkopar.<br>11:34 pm - Thane.<br>11:57 pm - Dombivali.<br>12:07 am - Kalyan.<br>01:18 am - Kasara.<br><br><b>3rd February (Saturday):</b><br>01:30 am - Depart to base village ie Samrad by a Private Vehicle.<br>04:00 am - Reach Samrad. Proceed for some rest and breakfast in the morning.<br>07:00 am - Move towards the entry point exploring Sandhan Valley. Rappel down a few patches. Lunch mid way.<br><br><b>05:30 pm - Reach the camping area.</b><